# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: obix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:obix/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:obix/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:obix/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:obix/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:obix/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:obix/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:obix/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:obix/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:obix/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:obix/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:obix/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:obix/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:obix/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:obix/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:obix/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:obix/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:obix/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:obix/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:obix/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:obix/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:obix/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:obix/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:obix/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:obix/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:obix/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:obix/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:obix/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:obix/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:obix/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:obix/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:obix/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:obix/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:obix/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:obix/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:obix/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:obix/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:obix/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:obix/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:obix/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:obix/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:obix/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:obix/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:obix/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:obix/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:obix/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:obix/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:obix/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:obix/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:obix/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:obix/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:obix/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:obix/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:obix/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:obix/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:obix/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:obix/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:obix/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:obix/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:obix/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:obix/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:obix/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:obix/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:obix/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:obix/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:obix/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:obix/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:obix/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:obix/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:obix/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:obix/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:obix/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:obix/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:obix/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:obix/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:obix/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:obix/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:obix/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:obix/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:obix/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:obix/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:obix/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:obix/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:obix/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:obix/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:obix/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:obix/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:obix/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:obix/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:obix/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:obix/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:obix/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:obix/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:obix/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:obix/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:obix/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:obix/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:obix/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:obix/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:obix/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:obix/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:obix/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:obix/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:obix/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:obix/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:obix/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:obix/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:obix/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:obix/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:obix/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:obix/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:obix/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:obix/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:obix/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:obix/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:obix/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:obix/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:obix/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:obix/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:obix/extensible-markup-language] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:obix/obix] oBIX is a web services interface because it does not necessarily allow deep interactions with the underlying control systems.
[src:obix/obix] This interface can enable communications between enterprise applications and embedded building systems as well as between two embedded building systems.
[src:obix/obix] Facilities and their operations to be managed as full participants in knowledge-based businesses.
[src:obix/obix] oBIX is being developed within OASIS, the Organization for the Advancement of Structured Information Standards.
[src:obix/obix] Version 1.0 was completed as a committee standard in December 2006.
[src:obix/obix] Presently most mechanical and electrical systems are provided with embedded digital controls (DDC).
[src:obix/obix] Most of these devices are low cost and not enabled for TCP/IP.
[src:obix/obix] They are installed with dedicated communications wiring.
[src:obix/obix] Larger DDC controllers provide network communications for these dedicated controllers.
[src:obix/obix] There are many well established binary protocols (BACnet, LonTalk, Modbus, DALI) that are used on these dedicated networks in addition to numerous proprietary protocols.
[src:obix/obix] While these binary protocols can be used over TCP/IP networks - they have challenges with routers, firewalls, security, and compatibility with other network applications.
[src:obix/obix] There is an added challenge in that the industry is split between several largely incompatible protocols.
[src:obix/obix] Because oBIX integrates with the enterprise, it enables mechanical and electrical control systems to provide continuous visibility of operational status and performance.
[src:obix/obix] oBIX provides a publicly available web services interface specification that can be used to obtain data in a simple and secure manner from HVAC, access control, utilities, and other building automation systems, and to provide data exchange between facility systems and enterprise applications.
[src:obix/obix] oBIX 1.0 provides a low level object model which can be extended during implementation.
[src:obix/obix] While points are directly addressable (and thereby settable), direct interaction with the points requires too much knowledge of the underlying control system for the enterprise developer.
[src:obix/obix] The underlying points can be aggregated, the results named, alarm levels set, and histories begun using the oBIX **contract**.
[src:obix/obix] If oBIX exposes a low level object model for control systems, oBIX contracts create the higher level type libraries that most programmers actually want to work with.
[src:obix/obix] To keep a public space open in the evening may require a range of calls to different organizations within a building, each initiating an interaction with a separate building control system.
[src:obix/obix] In an oBIX-enabled building, these features are accomplished by instead sending an iCalendar meeting invitation to the room and/or its support systems.
[src:obix/obix] The Common Alerting Protocol (CAP) is a standard increasingly used for relaying information from various agencies to the public and to police and first responders.
[src:obix/obix] One challenge that public notification faces is that the traditional Emergency Broadcasting System for transmitting information over the radio is now much less effective, now that the public is tuned instead to personal media players such as the iPod.
[src:obix/obix] New versions of these protocols anticipate, for example, direct texting of all cell phones in range of a given cell tower or set of cell towers.
[src:obix/obix] In a similar manner, current proposals suggest direct messaging to Intelligent Buildings to invoke named oBIX contracts, with effects ranging from temporary user security elevation, to initiating process shut down, to notifying in-building warning systems to read messages aloud.
[src:obix/obix] The Open Geospatial Consortium anticipates Emergency Responders being able to access certain classes of geo-tagged sensor information from buildings from within their maps to improve situational awareness.
[src:obix/obix] The GridWise Architecture Council envisions an open market or Power Providers, Transmission, Distribution, and Customer Agents negotiating freely for live power contracts based on instantaneous demand/response.
[src:obix/obix] The ongoing installation across the US of Electric Meters able to provide time-of-day-metering is one step to enabling this.
[src:obix/obix] Another is the development of Intelligent Buildings able to negotiate with the grid.
[src:obix/obix] These grid negotiations are likely to be of two forms.
[src:obix/obix] (1) An intelligent agent residing in the building, and negotiating with the building tenants and their business processes negotiates set building system operating postures.
[src:obix/obix] (2) An external agent hired by the building tenants aggregates demand across multiple buildings and buys power on their behalf.
[src:obix/obix] Markets based on these interactions are considered to be key to creating market conditions to drive rapid innovation in on-site power storage and generation technologies.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:obix/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:obix/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:obix/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:obix/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:obix/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:obix/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:obix/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:obix/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:obix/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:obix/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:obix/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:obix/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:obix/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:obix/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:obix/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:obix/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:obix/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:obix/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:obix/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:obix/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:obix/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:obix/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:obix/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:obix/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:obix/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:obix/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:obix/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:obix/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:obix/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:obix/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:obix/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:obix/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:obix/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:obix/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:obix/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:obix/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:obix/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:obix/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:obix/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:obix/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:obix/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:obix/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:obix/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:obix/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:obix/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
